ğŸš€ Quick Start
Prerequisites
You'll need these installed on your system:

Python 3.8+
Git
Visual Studio Code (recommended)

Installation
# Clone the repository
git clone [https://github.com/your-username/quantum-drug-discovery.git](https://github.com/your-username/quantum-drug-discovery.git)
cd quantum-drug-discovery

# Create and activate a virtual environment
python -m venv quantum_env
# Windows:
quantum_env\Scripts\activate
# macOS/Linux:
source quantum_env/bin/activate

# Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# Run the application
python app.py

ğŸŒ Access the Platform
Once the server is running, open your web browser and go to: http://localhost:5000

ğŸ³ Run with Docker
Donâ€™t want to mess with Python versions? Use Docker! ğŸš€

Build & Run
# Build image
docker build -t quantum-drug-discovery .

# Run container
docker run -p 5000:5000 quantum-drug-discovery

With Docker Compose
docker-compose up --build

ğŸ‘‰ Access app at: http://localhost:5000

ğŸ“± How to Use the Platform
1. ğŸ§  Train Your Quantum Model
Navigate to the "Train Quantum Model" section. Adjust the parameters to fit your dataset:

Dataset Size: Recommended 300-800 molecules for optimal performance.

Training Epochs: The number of iterations for the model to learn.

Learning Rate: Determines how quickly the model's weights are updated.

Click "Start Quantum Training" to begin the process.

2. ğŸ”¬ Test Molecular Properties
In the "Molecular Analysis" section, you can predict the effectiveness of a new molecule. Enter its key characteristics, such as:

Molecular Weight: 100-800 Da (Daltons)

LogP: -2 to 6 (lipophilicity measure)

Polar Surface Area: 20-200 Å² (drug absorption)

H-Bond Donors: 0-10 (binding capability)

Click "Analyze Molecule" to get an instant prediction.

